---
/**
 * domain-agent-design 0001 · Figure 1 — "One template · nine parts · same order".
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from
 * docs/domain-agent-design/lessons/0001-the-domain-agent-design-method.html
 * (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the footnote <sup id="r1b">). Lives as an
 * .astro component because MDX's JSX parser is unreliable with raw inline SVG
 * that uses kebab-case attributes; in .astro the SVG is plain HTML so it renders
 * byte-for-byte.
 *
 * In the source HTML the arrowhead markers (#arw, #arwG, #arwR, #arwM) are
 * defined ONCE in a body-level <svg width="0" height="0"> defs block and shared
 * by every figure. Now that each figure is an isolated component, the markers it
 * references are embedded as a local <defs> in THIS svg so url(#…) resolves
 * (marker refs resolve per-SVG-document, so the ids do not collide across the
 * separate figure components). This figure uses #arw and #arwG.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 330"
        role="img"
        aria-label="The nine-part domain agent design template arranged in order: responsibilities, tools, context, memory, runtime, evaluation, security, approval gates, ROI — with boundary first and ROI last."
    >
        <defs>
            <marker
                id="arw"
                viewBox="0 0 10 10"
                refX="8.5"
                refY="5"
                markerWidth="7"
                markerHeight="7"
                orient="auto-start-reverse"
                ><path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="#6b675f"></path></marker
            >
            <marker
                id="arwG"
                viewBox="0 0 10 10"
                refX="8.5"
                refY="5"
                markerWidth="7"
                markerHeight="7"
                orient="auto-start-reverse"
                ><path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="#2f5d3a"></path></marker
            >
        </defs>
        <text x="320" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >One template &middot; nine parts &middot; same order every domain</text
        >

        <!-- the nine numbered parts as a 3x3 grid of chips -->
        <!-- row 1 -->
        <rect
            x="30"
            y="40"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#eceef9"
            stroke="#3d54c9"
            stroke-width="1.8"></rect>
        <text x="120" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#3d54c9"
            >1 &middot; Responsibilities</text
        >
        <text x="120" y="76" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f">the boundary</text>
        <rect
            x="230"
            y="40"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#eceef9"
            stroke="#3d54c9"
            stroke-width="1.8"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#3d54c9"
            >2 &middot; Tools</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="76" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f">the surface</text>
        <rect
            x="430"
            y="40"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#f4f4f6"
            stroke="#6b675f"
            stroke-width="1.2"></rect>
        <text x="520" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >3 &middot; Context</text
        >
        <text x="520" y="76" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f">the window</text>
        <!-- row 2 -->
        <rect
            x="30"
            y="100"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#f4f4f6"
            stroke="#6b675f"
            stroke-width="1.2"></rect>
        <text x="120" y="120" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >4 &middot; Memory</text
        >
        <text x="120" y="136" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >persisted state</text
        >
        <rect
            x="230"
            y="100"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#f4f4f6"
            stroke="#6b675f"
            stroke-width="1.2"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="120" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >5 &middot; Runtime</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="136" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f">the loop</text>
        <rect
            x="430"
            y="100"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#f4f4f6"
            stroke="#6b675f"
            stroke-width="1.2"></rect>
        <text x="520" y="120" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >6 &middot; Evaluation</text
        >
        <text x="520" y="136" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >how you score it</text
        >
        <!-- row 3 -->
        <rect
            x="30"
            y="160"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#fbecec"
            stroke="#9a2417"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="120" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >7 &middot; Security</text
        >
        <text x="120" y="196" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >untrusted input</text
        >
        <rect
            x="230"
            y="160"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#fbecec"
            stroke="#9a2417"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >8 &middot; Approval gates</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="196" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >by blast radius</text
        >
        <rect
            x="430"
            y="160"
            width="180"
            height="48"
            rx="9"
            fill="#e9f3ec"
            stroke="#2f5d3a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="520" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >9 &middot; ROI / build-buy</text
        >
        <text x="520" y="196" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f">ship or kill</text>

        <!-- ordering spine -->
        <line
            x1="120"
            y1="208"
            x2="120"
            y2="236"
            stroke="#6b675f"
            stroke-dasharray="3 3"
            marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line
            x1="320"
            y1="208"
            x2="320"
            y2="236"
            stroke="#6b675f"
            stroke-dasharray="3 3"
            marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line
            x1="520"
            y1="208"
            x2="520"
            y2="236"
            stroke="#2f5d3a"
            stroke-dasharray="3 3"
            marker-end="url(#arwG)"></line>

        <rect x="30" y="238" width="580" height="34" rx="8" fill="#eceef9" stroke="#3d54c9"></rect>
        <text x="320" y="253" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#3d54c9"
            >Boundary (1) sets the surface (2) &rarr; surface sets the risk (6&ndash;7) &rarr; risk
            sets the gates (8) &rarr; value decides ship (9)</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="266" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >Parts 3&ndash;5 are the machinery the agent runs on; 1&ndash;2 and 8&ndash;9 are the
            design decisions you own.</text
        >

        <text x="320" y="296" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-style="italic" fill="#3d54c9"
            >Per-domain lessons (billing, SRE, research&hellip;) don't reinvent this &mdash; they
            fill it in.</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="320" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >The more an agent can do unsupervised, the more an approval gate matters.</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        The method on one page. You walk the nine parts <em>in order</em> because each one constrains
        the next: the boundary decides the tool surface, the surface decides the blast radius, the blast
        radius decides where humans sign off, and the ROI test decides whether you build it at all.<sup
            ><a href="#s1" id="r1b">1</a></sup
        >
    </figcaption>
</figure>
